verbose_text: The finding that VPS34-IN1 does not suppress activity of SGK2 that does not possess a PtdIns (3) P binding PX domain (XREF_FIG C) is also consistent with the notion that the ability of VPS34-IN1 to suppress SGK3 is dependent on its ability to bind PtdIns (3) P. SGK3 was first identified as a novel isoform of SGK1 [XREF_BIBR] that played a role in enabling the IL (interleukin)-3-dependent survival of haemopoietic cells [XREF_BIBR].
evidence: VPS34-IN1 does not suppress activity of SGK2
